reviews.text: We visited in the morning on a bright upbeat day and had a tour guide. We were not allowed access as exam time, so that was a bit of a disappointing. Having said that this is one of the star colleges and views from the riverside are very good, may have to zoom in a bit to get a good photograph. From the front of the college views are nice and great

One of the must see destinations for Cambridge. Beautiful grounds and stunning views abound around this whimsical and enchanting place. It cost a few pounds to get in, but if you know a student they can get you in for free 😉
One of the must-see pieces of architecture in Cambridge. Very old and very unique. Get there early to avoid people walking in front of your camera taking pictures.

King's College of the University of Cambridge. Formally The King's College of Our Lady and Saint Nicholas in Cambridge, the college lies beside the River Cam and faces out onto King's Parade in the centre of the city. King's was founded in 1441 by Henry VI. The building of the college's chapel, begun in 1446, was finally finished in 1544 during the reign of Henry VIII. It's regarded as one of the greatest examples of late Gothic English architecture. The chapel's stained-glass windows and wooden chancel screen are considered some of the finest from their era.

reviews.author_name: Allain Jing Couple in Love world travels
reviews.text: This is a must see in Cambridge, Kings college is one of the most visited tourist spot here. You can also walk around and is is best place for photography. We enjoyed taking pictures and posing like a model because f the unique place.

For just £3 you get to walk round the beautiful grounds of one of Cambridge's college. 

Some great architecture and wonderful greenery, bridges going over the river cam to watch the people punting.

When in the early evening and the colours are just spectacular.
One of the more well-known colleges in Cambridge with a large college ground near the city centre. Look out for the famed Newton's apple tree outside the college too!

Firstly I would like to say that the hospitality I received here would perhaps have been familiar to an Eastern European under a Mongul invasion. The porters hurled racist and sexist abuse to my grandmother and proceeded to give the wrong directions to the chapel. I am utterly disgusted and would not recommend to anyone

Had an old friend over, and it was her first and probably would be her only time ever in Cambridge, and they turned her away from taking a look at the college (quite rudely). My friend is in her 70s. It was classless.
Beautiful buildings and atmosphere

A beautiful college worth visiting even though it is a few minutes walk from the city centre. I love the horse sculpture in the middle of the courtyard which provides a different view at different angles. Large green courtyards and amazing architecture.
Got in for free which is not necessarily typical for cambridge colleges. Walking around the greens was beautiful
Unbelievable place. So perfect.
It was a bit difficult to find the lodging but otherwise great

Jesus college thinks that it is pretty great. And to be fair, it is pretty great. They have some interesting statues including a life-sized horse that students often climb on when drunk. Do not climb on the statues.

Clare College is rather hidden even though it is located in the city centre. It is undergoing some refurbishment at the moment and seems to be perpetually closed to public. But if you manage to get in, it is a small yet pretty little college. Take a stroll along the bridge and count the number of round stones on it! You can also get a good view of the unique Jerwood Library from there.
Beautiful sunny day to enjoy the grounds. No longer free like it once was !

While I was here, the janitor John asked me to help him with carrying tools. I fell down and when I woke up, I was tied to his bed. He appeared before me in a leather suit and pulled out a belt, then he pulled out something else... 

sub to bird lizard on utube
Great selection of whisky in the mcr bar, larger selection than any other bar in Cambridge.
Excellent place - i am in love with this place.

A small college next to the King's college, but worth a visit. It has a grand gate at the entrance, and a wall of lovely autumn leaves at the side if you visit during the right season. A stunning symmetrical main building and courtyard.
Lovely green in the heart of the city.

It's a beautiful place to stay in, I've been here for the past month and it's been fantastic. Food is also very inexpensive and quite pleasant. Would recommend to anyone staying at Cambridge for long periods.
Small friendly college. Very helpful staff and lovely location. Recommended.
Understated but very beautiful college.

Lovely college in Cambridge which you can visit along the way to the market square! It has a small and pretty little chapel within. Don't forget to check out the famous Corpus Clock outside of the college too!

An amazing place to study my undergraduate. They gave me an insight into the subject which I wasn't previously aware of! Great stuff, guys. 
My one and ONLY crit is that can be a bit small and cramped at times, but oh well, never mind! I miss my studies here, wish I could go back.
beautiful architecture
Beautiful with the punks, the lake and the genuine church around, you can feel the team university soul and the student atmosphere

I did a lovely adult course here.

It is so beautiful inside.  You students don't realize how lucky you lot are.

Wonderful place.

Always a beautiful walk. This garden is truly worth a visit if you haven't been inside. I work close by and get to walk around daily but it never ceases to amaze me. The care and effort that they put into maintaining it is truly amazing and a wonderful work of art. The staff are generally friendly and very helpful.

Beautiful haven in the middle of the city. It's a great place to take children. There's a café and plenty of space for picnics. Our children particularly like walking through the glasshouse. It's an inexpensive day out, close to the train station for travelers, and we all recommend it.

Good to visit different times of the year as it is different plants blooming. Ticket is affordable. There is shop and toilets at the entrance. And information of the most interesting things to visit at the time. Can be found plants and flowers from all around the globe. The Greenhouse itself is big and the most beautiful. Reccomend for everyone.
Absolutely fabulous. So much to see and kept my attention the whole visit.   Left for food and came back in.  Big plus and bought some plants.  it was a mother's day present and we live in Yorkshire

Beautiful gardens. Lovely afternoon in Cambridge if it's nice weather. The glass houses are by far the best part.

The cafes a tad pricey (even for Cambridge) but is a nice place to stop and sit.

Huge expanse of open space, ideal if you want space for kids to run around or just take in some rays. Otherwise there's a shared pathway for pedestrians and cyclists which crisscrosses the park. Pathways are desperately in need of repair, potholes everywhere (April 2019). Maybe a few more trees, water features/art/statues might make the park more attractive.
Green green, flat flat. Nothing to exciting really,  but I always appreciate large green grounds in the city centre. Good place for picnics and games. Otherwise, just stroll by.
It's a big green space. Have fun! Check out the lamp post in the middle for some hidden art. There's also instructions for football carved into stone, in case you're not sure what to do.
The place where the modern game of football came into existence. Come for it's great panaromic sunsets or it's winter carnival
Lovely wide expanse of lawn. A pleasure to walk to or from YMCA or swim pools to the old city, parking at their Multi Story (simple contactless payment)

Absolutely amazing. The exhibits were so well presented and laid out so even a museum newbie like me could find and see everything I wanted. The Egyptian exhibition was especially brilliant. Oh and the building itself is so beautiful. I would 100% recommend any one to go. It is free to get in but they do have a donations box. Great place for a cheap but cultural date

Great nauseam. There is a wide variety of artwork. So if you have specific interests you will probably find one of the gallery's really interesting. The entry is free. They have a nice cafe where you can get something to eat and drink. With a gift shop right beside it.

One of the best museums outside of London, it really is a museum of world history, think British museum or Liverpool's world museum.

The building itself is beautiful, it is a work of art in itself especially the main entrance and stairwell when it reopen

It has a huge variety of exhibits covering different cultures like Greece, Rome, Egypt etc. Showing everything from sculptures to paintings, pots, sarcophagus and anything else you can imagine.

Great café and a decent sized gift shop as well.

Only downside is that sometimes things just seem to be grouped together just because. A little bit more thought about the layout of the exhibits could really help this place.

But it's free, clean, modern and you could easily lose half a day in here.
We were only there for 2 hours but really enjoyed the art. Will return to Cambridge and the museum one day. Fabulous!
Great place. Clean and tidy.Very friendly staff. Perfect place to spent time alone and with family.Nice art work to be found on second floor of museum. Entry-absolutely for Free.

This is a tremendously informative museum. There is a display on Charles Darwin and from there it gives a chronological overview of history from Cambrian time, around 560 million years ago to today. 
Each section has an overview of climate, types of creatures that appeared and what the continents or continent looked like along with a ton of fossils. There are literally thousands on display. There is also a T-Rex skull and who doesn't love seeing s T-Rex.
It's a really good place to spend the afternoon m

Really wonderful exhibition of items and dinosaur bones.
I never seen a T. rex skull until now so I was quite surprised, I really enjoyed my experience and is shall hope to come again soon.
My children loved this museum! Free entry. There is a lift to avoid dragging prams up the stone steps! Well worth a visit

An ocean of information packed in this Sedgwick Museum about Jurrasic world / Dinosaurs. If you are you dinosaurs lover living in Cambridge, then this is a must go place. Prepare your self to spend at least half a day / full day if you want explore each and every bit of dinosaurs. Its free to enter. I highly recommend this museum for all age groups. Thank you.
Lots to see, very well displayed. Lovely museum.

This is a tremendously informative museum. There is a display on Charles Darwin and from there it gives a chronological overview of history from Cambrian time, around 560 million years ago to today. 
Each section has an overview of climate, types of creatures that appeared and what the continents or continent looked like along with a ton of fossils. There are literally thousands on display. There is also a T-Rex skull and who doesn't love seeing s T-Rex.
It's a really good place to spend the afternoon m

Really wonderful exhibition of items and dinosaur bones.
I never seen a T. rex skull until now so I was quite surprised, I really enjoyed my experience and is shall hope to come again soon.
My children loved this museum! Free entry. There is a lift to avoid dragging prams up the stone steps! Well worth a visit

An ocean of information packed in this Sedgwick Museum about Jurrasic world / Dinosaurs. If you are you dinosaurs lover living in Cambridge, then this is a must go place. Prepare your self to spend at least half a day / full day if you want explore each and every bit of dinosaurs. Its free to enter. I highly recommend this museum for all age groups. Thank you.
Lots to see, very well displayed. Lovely museum.

A priceless resource for the classics student and great little past time. It costs nothing to go in and walk around. The volunteers are kind and informative. The pieces are replicas of some of the worlds most renowned examples of Classical Greek and Roman sculpture that you'd have to travel the world to see all the originals but here they are all in one place and retain their colossal size and grandeur!
Though mostly, if not all, are plaster copies, this is a good place to see some of the popular sculptures. The staff are very friendly and the place is also good  place to relax.
Unique collection of the classic periods of sculpture.
Had a good time kids enjoyed it you can go round in an hour so you won't be able to loose hours there,  staff very friendly

Great selection of marble statues and other trinkets. Many of the statues had their bits knocked off in the past for reasons of modesty. I imagine, somewhere, there's a large collection of statue-bits.

I've read a fair amount about polar exploration, particularly around the race to the South pole but seeing articles from the expeditions in person made it feel that much realer and somehow better convey the hardships suffered.

The museum also covered the native peoples of the Arctic, to whom the Arctic and its difficulties was just daily life, and their interactions with those seeking the Northwest Passage which was really interesting to see more about.

I think it would have been better to expand a bit further on the work that the Institute and others are doing around Polar research today and maybe link it more directly back to the scientific work done by the early explorers but otherwise I think it was excellent.

It's small (an hour if you get into it), but well done. You could perhaps get the same information and photos of the same objects on Wikipedia. But this is very well curated, it's all interesting, and there's something to be said for seeing actual objects. I wouldn't go to Cambridge for this, but if you're there...
Fantastic collection, genuinely interesting. Great activities for children as part of the science open day.
It is nice to learn a bit about the wonderful expeditions to the poles. It is very small though and not interactive.

I liked it it has things which were surrealistic and mythical to me before seeing it. Must visit it! I bought a compass from it's merch(it's with me ;)  The museum It's a bit small and conjusted I would say.
Was closed but looked good from outside

Such a superb place to visit. So much to see ... so much to learn .... allowing you to get up close to our industrial past ... imagining the workers of gone by ... for us now ... maybe a nostalgic looking back of our heritage and skills ... but in reality I think it would of being backbreaking work ... the chimney .. you can only look in awe as it dominates the Cambridge skies .. staff so very friendly and knowledgeable.

Museum of Technology enhanced with Thirsty Biergarten. Wonderful place if you want to hang out with family and friends. German beer and a nice collection of street food, coffee, ice cream, macaron... this could be one of the best place for summer. Bit expensive though...

Attempted to go in, finding opening hours to be three hours in the afternoon to be a narrow window.  Arrived to find that it was three hours in the afternoon on Sundays only; during the summer.

Winter hours are three hours on one Sunday each moth.

That said it did look fascinating on the outside.
Enjoyed a lot👌

For £4 you can go inside to see the church but most interestingly go up the 100 plus steps to the top for some really great views of Cambridge. They have a good set-up with metal fences to stop people jumping but they have holes in them allowing you to take photos. 1 of the best valued tourist spots in Cambridge.
It was a really Great place to visit! The history was well documented, the church and its interior as well as its surroundings were so well kept. A must to visit.
It is a really nice place to visit in the Cambridge. It a spotlight to see over view of all city from the top. Just £5
Visited Great St Mary's Church for Holocaust Memorial civic ceremony. It is a beautiful old church based in the heart of Cambridge. Well worth a visit if you are passing.

The church has an tower with a great view that you can see all Cambridge.
To visit the church (that is also beautiful) it's for free but to go on the tower it's onyl five pounds.
Nice old English Gothic architecture but no longer functioning as a church. Usual venues for special college events and exhibitions.

Stunning Bodley church with windows by Kempe, William Morris, Burne-Jones and Madox Brown. A Bodley church throughout from candlesticks to pews to fabric, grandly decorated and retaining a medieval muted light. Opening hours are subject to change but it's usually open Mon-Fri 11:00-15:00 during term time.

It was very nice there.   Out in the countryside, got there as part of the hop on-off bus.   Looks to see and lot of information in the visitor center.  Spend a good hour or 2 here.  Is very peaceful.  Worthy of a visit.

The Cambridge American Cemetery and Memorial site in England, 30.5 acres in total, was donated by the University of Cambridge. The cemetery contains the remains of 3,812 of our war dead; 5,127 names are recorded on the Walls of the Missing. Most died in the Battle of the Atlantic or in the strategic air bombardment of northwest Europe.

 Along the south side are the Walls of the Missing with four great sculptures. At the far end is the memorial with a chapel, two huge military maps, stained glass windows bearing the state seals and military decorations, and a mosaic ceiling memorial honoring the dead of our air forces.

A new, 4,000-square-foot center visitor center opened in May 2014. There is also a free Cambridge American Cemetery smartphone app with suggested tours of the cemetery, maps, history, and other important details about the site

We had a very poignant day at Madingley honouring Staff Sgt Harry W Estabrooks, Sgt Maurice D Robbins and Sgt Charles H Tuttle and the other seven crew members of ‘Mi Amigo’ whose B-17 came down in Endcliffe Park, Sheffield 75 years ago. 
At Endcliffe Park yesterday, 10,000 people gathered to mark the event which  fulfilled the lifelong dream of 82-year-old Tony Foulds, who was eight years old when he saw the bomber crash into the woods next to where he and his friends were playing. 
Shortly after the service at Madingley, the flight of 4 F-15 Strike Eagles from RAF Lakenheath flew over the Cemetery in a very tight formation against a beautiful blue sky on their way back from the ceremony in Sheffield - a very fitting tribute.
Graves are comfy. Nice gravedigger

Beautiful and well maintained. The cemetery and memorial itself are a fantastic visit. However, the 16:30 taps ceremony was disgraceful. The staff member carrying out said ceremony did not fold the flag and instead elected to screw it into a ball and then lay it on the bench by the visitor centre.
A favourite place of ours to walk. Parkland is great.. Interesting house, super little animal farm. Can get very busy in school holidays & weekends.
House magnificent, bit short on exhibits. Farm, gardens & playground excellent for children. A good family day out.

Fantastic place to let the children run off steam, see lots of different animals, and be out in the fresh air. Always different events, or activities in which to take part, and entry is free for NT members.

First time at Wimpole estate today and was really impressed. Easy to get round and has a working farm to walk round. Daughter loved seeing the piglets and shire horses. Really nice gardens and house is really interesting. Plenty of countryside to stroll around in as well. Staff friendly and helpful as always with national trust places.
Lots to see and do. We spent the day at Home Farm and the play area and the kids had a blast. Service was a bit slow at the home farm cafe, they seemed surprised to be busy on a sunny spring day...

My own experience here was a most enjoyable evening of music. The venue has limitations because of its age. It was a Corn Exchange after all, so such things as queue for the ladies being in the same place as access down stairs to the bar are unavoidable. Having said that, it is a beautiful - at least to me - historic building and the limitations add to its charm. Be aware that obstructed view tickets really are what they say.

Nice venue, not too big so even if you have back row seats don't worry you will get a great view.. ...no seats in front of the stage it's standing only. Bar gets very busy, reasonably priced considering its Cambridge. Toilets bit random, men one side of the stage and women the other side, I walked into the men's by accident then found out I had to walk right round to the other side!!
Great place to see a show! would highly recommend! Would definitely advise a seat near the front of the balcony for best viewing!
Took my mum to see Julian Clary's Born to Mince tour as a birthday present and pick-me-up. Enjoyed the show, fabulous filth at the Cambridge Corn exchange. Very friendly and helpful staff.
Great venue with some great acts. Always well managed entrance and exiting and bar always well run. A great place to see whatever show as all views are good, even at the very top not the balcony

Very bad atmosphere, basically it is a wet and humid cellar. 
Food was just ok, I had their special spinach lasagna. It was extremely fat, and the taste despite of so much oil consumption was nothing spectacular. Nothing like a calm and nice atmosphere you expect from any cafe. If you care about dishes and glasses of cafe, again forget about it here. Nothing fits in terms of harmony or beauty of space.
A very bad choice if you are claustrophobic.
>> I added this 3 years after: Reading the answer of the restaurant, will tell you way more things about their attitude as well. Go down and check all their responses to not positive reviews, mine was a bad day, somebody had a bad sleep. Extremely professional!

This place is a hidden gem. Understated from the street with its little overhead colourful sign and easily missed.. But... Miss it at your loss, because inside the homely, casual, eclectic basement you will discover food that's nourishing with a home-cooked, individual simplicity that hits the spot everytime.  We couldn't fault anything from the delicious drinks,  simple refreshing salads, flavour--bursting soups and good wholesome mains.  And if you're after cake or pud.. Wow.. How do they do it? A particular favourite of mine .. The black forest vegan cheesecake.. I honestly don't think I've ever had a better dessert! This place is a vegetarian and vegans heaven so find that rainbow and discover the culinary pot of gold that awaits you 🌈

My daughter took me here. Hidden away this unique little place, is tranquil, relaxing and exquisite.
The food is excellent, with a wide choice and very good value for money.
Can't wait to go again.

Friendly restaurant. We had lasagna, but I found it tasteless. Good ingredients but unmerged. Probably the desserts were better. A lot of people and everybody seemed satisfied, what makes us think that we were unlucky with our choice. They are not the fastest ones.

While vegetarian venues are becoming more common, this is one of the originals! There is a wide variety of food on the standard menu and a specials list which changes regularly (both mains and desserts!)

Obviously everything is vegetarian, but there is also a good selection of vegan options and everything is labelled with allergens, making it very easy to know what is what.

The mains were delicious and the dessert was to die for!
Great service for our large group, very friendly and capable staff. Great little bistro, simple, good food and coffee.

Quiet yet vibrant atmosphere, solid menu of  art tasty. Service is a little lukewarm sometimes but I'm sure that is for efficiency (food come quick).

Nice place to have tea or meal with friends.
My husband and I enjoyed our time together at the CB2. Nice atmosphere, brilliant service and the food was the best I had. We go there quite often and we were never disappointed. Great restaurant!
Hip !! Good music friendly staff
Good food, large portions. Good service.
Fabolous fish and chips. Price is adequate to the quality of food. I suggest you to try. A wonderful a experience. I take also a superb IPA beer. I hope to go back soon as possible

Great restaurant right by the Senate house (and not touristy at all). Excellent service and good food - The club sandwich was tasty and very filling. However my husband had the special which was pork belly and, although it was also delicious, the portion was so so tiny for a main!  The lovely waiter was brilliant though - we didn't get round to even mentioning this issue when he came back and apologised for the small portion and gave us a round of free truffled old fashioned shots (very good by the way) and some olives and took some off the bill. Definitely redeemed the situation and would recommend!

Worst ever lunch I’ve ever had. Old chip fat that we stunk of when I left. I didn’t pay for one meal as it was awful and inedible. So many nice places to eat in Cambridge and I think this has to be my worst meal I’ve ever had in Cambridge. DO NOT EAT HERE. Over priced bad food. Some of the staff were rude and ordered a beef burger instead of a veggie burger, what an awful mistake to make putting a beef burger in front of a vegan.
Close to St Marks Church, good food but often busy. If you're okay with this then I recommend it.
Pleasant place with good food.  Main issue was they were out of various items too early in the evening.  No excuse to be out of menu items.
I've been a parent at this school for 12 years and it has always done us proud. A wonderful caring, nurturing, inclusive school with great staff in a fantastic spacious setting.
This school has wonderful spaces, inspiring teachers and my children are happy - what more could you want?

Exquisite steak and excellent wine. Along with Blackadder playing in the toilets, the atmosphere is excellent. I’ve been here about once a year for the entire time I’ve been in Cambridge and I’ve never come away disappointed. It’s great for a special occasion or if you just love steak. The staff are brilliant and know how to deliver good customer service. You won’t be disappointed - I can guarantee that.

Great Sunday lunch for a large family group in a perfect Cambridge location. 3 generations, from 7 months to 7 decades old were booked in and welcomed warmly. 

Our tables were in an atmospheric private room in the converted cellar, which was great fun. Special choices were catered for with no fuss (and our 2 veggies were able to find something to suit them). The roasts were hot, fresh and tasty! 

A great find for us (new) locals, and an ideal choice to take weekend visitors :-)

Exceptionally good food and service in a converted cellar / rustic setting that adds to the experience.

Food: their steaks are delicious, and so are their fish. Decent dessert options, but they could probably improve on that point.

Very good service: they kindly accommodated vegetarians and a few people with strict dietary requirements.

Atmosphere: feels like you're eating in an old, charming place, and with the benefits of having clean, modern tables, utensils, etc. great setting overall, really helps the experience.

Fabulous food with a fabulous view. Situated on King's Parade opposite the iconic King's College, the Chop House is a great place for people-watching. The food is always tasty, and they offer a good selection of wines and beers. My favourite dish is the Butler steak.
This is a restaurant I'm happy to visit again and again.
Consistent excellent service and delicious food. We've been to several of their restaurants over the years and have always enjoyed our meals.  Definitely our 'go to' place when we dine in town.

Tests on its laurels. The food is just okay and there isn't much option of bakery items. Service is fairly brash. The seating is kind of hard and bathrooms without much love. But then, it's not outrageously expensive. The site is well placed on a main tourist route so does get busy, but on the plus side it is convenient to access.

Fitzbillies is fabulous but be prepared to queue and wait for a table because it is so popular there. 
The Chelsea buns are renowned for their sumptuous gooey-ness but they are not as good as I remember them from my school days in the 70s when the dough was thinner with more tightly coiled rings and a clearer sugar syrup coating them. Still finger licking good though!

Do not leave Cambridge without visiting Fitzbillies for their super moreish sticky Chelsea Bun - also worth a mention is their Coffee Choux. It’s got to be one of the top 5 things to do if you are visiting! I’m a local but I still can’t walk past without scoffing one of buns!

The food quality to wait time ratio is quite skewed. You can find better breakfast at Indigo for cheaper. Also they don’t serve any other bread besides sourdough? This is 2019 and I have to eat sourdough?

I went here not to eat but just to buy the Chelsea Buns. It was recommended by my friend and I never regret it. I like the Chelsea buns, it's soft yet solid and the sweetness is not too much. To put it simply, it's Chelsea buns is so delicate. Furthermore, I only have to pay like £2 only. I recommend this place to you guys and don't forget to buy the Chelsea buns :))

We went for lunch and had a really good meal. I had the fish soup starter and the tuna main course.  Tuna was really nicely cooked.  Crisp glass of white to go with it. We enjoyed our visit as we always do here.  Minor gripe was £8.30 for large white wine which was a little steep, but overall our meals were decent value I thought.

Had dinner with my children tonight after the Twilight as the Museum in Cambridge (which is brilliant by the way). They fancied fish & chips, so that's what they had. I had fish soup & mussels. Beautiful food as always. Kids menu is £7 for 2 courses, £9 for 3, so completely affordable. However, not to worry because kids eat free during February half term (obviously, with paying adults). Everyone polished their plates. Waiter was lovely. The only reason it's not 5 star today is because we waited a bit for food, but the restaurant was very busy.

Visited this restaurant on March 28 with a friend and tasted their latest spring menu. 

Great seafood and atmosphere in this restaurant, had a seafood mixed grill as mains and mussels as starter. The seafood mixer was cooked to perfection, with the salmon and seabass fillet not overcooked and the scallop was tender. 
Went there with a 30% discount voucher for the whole table, which saved a lot of money as the prices on the menu are not cheap. Therefore recommend to check their website occasionally for discount vouchers and deals. Would be better if the website has pricing of the food listed on their menu

Overall a great dinning experience
The food is tasty here. Fresh seafood. And they know how to cook the fish in delicious way. I like their seafood platter, you can try a bit of everything.

Amazing sea food restaurant and such friendly, welcoming staff. It was my dad's birthday and they brought out a glass of prosecco for each of us. The food was stunning and, even though its not the cheapest, you get what you pay for. We will definitely be going back.

Amazing Thai food restaurant. This place has great food with huge portions and an amazing atmosphere as well. Would recommend the pineapple fried rice, the pad Thai and the mango sticky rice for dessert. The prices can be a little steep but the portions are so big that it'd always have sufficient leftovers that'll last me another meal. Would recommend asking for a box to pack your leftovers to make the meal more worth it. 

The service is great as well - the waiter is patient and polite, and the food arrived quite quickly as well.

Others reviews mention price is cheap but actually it's not cheap unless you go at lunchtime where they have a lunch deal. Price is pretty standard dinner prices, similar to Thai Khun. The dishes did seem very authentic and the presentation was good. 
Desserts were the only let down. Would recommend missing.
The food with large portions for a cheaper price is so amazing. It's very delicious. I also love the ambiance of the restaurant.

I had a really lovely experience here.
The staff were so so friendly and kind especially when I practiced some Thai on them.
Highly recommended the thong platter
Try not to giggle ordering that.

The spicy pineapple rice is a personal favourite of mine looks absolutely stunning plus its served in a pineapple.
Best (thai) restaurant in Cambridge. If you want something filling and quick, go for wok fried rice or noodles, they WILL fill you up. Curry/a la cate are more expensive but really worth it.
Excellent food. Very authentic flavours, great service and BYOB, which all makes for a very affordable and delicious meal! Not a single complaint, can't wait to come back :)
Staff was very friendly, no issues seating a party of 6 with no reservation during lunchtime. Food was delicious. My only complaint is that the portions are a little small.

The restaurant is very good . The main course dishes were excellent. The starters were also good. It is bit small restaurant, but it has tables in the basement also. Overall a nice place and u can always keep visiting it for it's excellent main course dishes.
Lovely food, well presented, by friendly and down to earth staff.

Not a card friendly place, doesn’t accept the card payment under 15GBPs ( doesn’t indicate anywhere). Portion is small and the taste is just normal. the waiter is good though. Tips counted in the bill.
Better chocolates than the Belgians! Top notch food, service and location. Wife is happy, that means I am too!  Outstanding.

3rd time dining at cotto last night and what an amazing chef they have! Every time the food has blown me away.  The staff are amazing and the atmosphere and setting is cosy and comfortable. My absolute favourite restaurant in the world!

A wonderful evening!. The food was outstanding and the staff were all you would expect for a fine dining experience. Alas the restaurant is only open for four days a week,but well worth a visit for special occasions or just to spoil yourself....

We had a great experience at Cotto. It started with a very warm welcome from the hostess and even the chef (Hans) came out to say hello. The ambience was fantastic. We enjoyed our 3-course dinner very much and did our own wine pairing. The wine list provided many high-quality choices. After the dinner we enjoyed cocktails at bar while listening to the piano. The place is certainly pricey but the price is justified given the outstanding quality.
Wonderful food and service, priced as you might expect for high quality dining. New venue has nice ambience.

Absolutely wonderful food. Great wine pairing with the bartender. Knew how to make his drinks. Young but incredibly experienced. The staff were friendly and the food was divine.

Small portions yes, but the food was packed with flavour, infact the portions were appropriate because too much of the intensive flavour would have been too much. 

This was absolutely perfect for a light lunch, don't expect something filling. This is a nice, quick treat. The reason I have given 4 stars is because I felt judged because I have tattoos, which is a shame because I am a paying customer and that should be the first perception of a customer.

Not what they look like.

Honestly speaking I really enjoyed this restaurant. Excellent food (as my pictures will show), amazing service, friendly staff and nice decor. I'd highly recommend this restaurant if you are looking for a great michelin-style restaurant experience. I went for the set-menu, being part of a group, the peach dessert was great and the lamb mains was also pretty good. My only disappointment was that they didn't serve cocktails on the menu, but for wine-lovers they had a very extensive wine menu. Nonetheless, I'd still give them five stars as everything else was pretty much perfect.

Food is alright but the design and set up of the restaurant is a little ‘cheesy’ music is strange like I am in a London bar in the city and the decor is boring and reminds me of an airport hotel. Its a shame because there is a lot of potential for this place. They need a renovation and a change of style.
Interesting and good eclectic food. Knowledgeable, friendly staff. Nice wines. Prix-fixe 3-course meal is a good deal.
Well worth a visit. Wonderful staff. Made to feel very welcome and a fantastic meal. Excellent value set lunch menu. Highly recommended.

I came to this quaint pub for some Thai food and I must say I was not disappointed. The Pork Chow Mein Noodle was amazing, with some nice vegetable garnish with some very respectable prices and lunch deals. Will be returning fairly soon!
I've eaten here twice. Both roast dinners were delicious and plentiful.  Really friendly staff.

We informed the staff of my friend’s nut allergy which they ignored and he consequently ended up in hospital. 
The staff were told, said they couldn’t guarantee anything - would’ve been great if they said that before serving the food! 
Avoid this place.

Homely and classic vibe. Excellent customer service very accommodating, professional staff. Excellent kitchen on sundays had the smokey burger perfectly seasoned packed with flavour and great value for money. Compliments to such a superb pub, my friends and I left very satisfied.
Always good. Decent beer, friendly staff, nice atmosphere.

Food was fantastic. Came for a birthday celebration. Was surprised with a sticky toffee pudding for dessert that was delicious. Restaurant was clean, with a comfortable atmosphere. Will definitely return.

Excellent food ! We went with a wedding party group of 12. We did wait about 1hr for our food. They had a good many people in there.  However, the staff was excellent and kept our drinks filled and fresh warm bread.  This is the second time we've been and have enjoyed it. I got the breaded chicken breast, stuffed with artichoke and provolone, topped with a creamy red pepper sauce. Hubby got the chicken parmesan and our friend got the prime rib with Yorkshire pudding.
Great place for a good dinner. Great place to have a party.

Food is delicious, pricey but quality is there. The interior is nicely designed and has more of a romantic ambience. Parking is very limited so that might become an issue. View is beautiful if you get a window seat with the view of the river.
Good food, do I need to say more?
